article.headline: St. John's 66, South Florida 62
article.story: NEW YORK (AP) -- Lamont Hamilton scored 20 points as St. John's built a big lead and then held off South Florida 66-62 on Wednesday night. Anthony Mason scored 13 points and Avery Patterson added 11 for the Red Storm (13-10, 4-6), who moved closer to their first Big East tournament spot in four seasons. The top 12 teams in the conference make the tournament at Madison Square Garden, and St. John's is tied with Connecticut and DePaul for the final three spots. The Red Storm haven't qualified since the 2002-03 season. Kentrell Gransberry scored 20 points and had 19 rebounds for the Bulls (12-11, 3-6), who in their second season in the conference still have a chance to make the playoffs for the first time. McHugh Mattis added 16 points, and Melvin Buckley had 15. Tomas Jasiulionis made two free throws for St. John's to make it 51-42 at 9:13. But South Florida scored seven unanswered points, including four by Gransberry, moving the Bulls within two, 51-49 at 13:31. The Red Storm responded with a 10-4 surge on two baskets each by Mason and Hamilton and Qa'rraan Calhoun's dunk to go up 59-53 at 16:48. The Bulls used a 6-2 run, capped by a 3-pointer by Buckley, to get within two again at 61-59 with 39 seconds left before St. John's sealed it with five free throws. After Jesus Verdejo connected on one of two free throws to give South Florida a 5-3 lead, St. John's went on a 27-10 run. Patterson led the surge with five points, including one of the Red Storm's five 3-pointers. After Buckley converted two free throws, the Red Storm went on a 10-2 run behind Hamilton's layup and 3-pointer for a 40-19 halftime lead. South Florida opened the second half with a 23-9 run behind Gransberry's 10 points to make it 49-42 at 10:25.
